      "is tight. For `k = 2`, `nthNat.Prime 2 = 3`, and `3 / (3 - 1) = 1.5 ‚â§ 3 / 2 = 1.5`. Again tight. For `k = 3`, `nthNat.Prime 3 = 5`, `5/4 ‚â§ 4/3 ‚âà 1.333`. Wait no, `5/4 = 1.25 ‚â§ 1.333`, so it holds. \n\nBut actually, for all `k ‚â• 1`, `nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k` is not always true. For example, for `k = 4`, `nthNat.Prime 4 = 7`, `7/6 ‚âà 1.166`, and `(4 + 1)/4 = 1.25`, so it holds. For `k = 5`, `nthNat.Prime 5 = 11`, `11/10 = 1.1 ‚â§ 6/5 = 1.2`, it holds again.\n\nBut this seems counter-intuitive because `nthNat.Prime k` grows much faster than `k + 1`, yet the ratio `nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1)` actually becomes closer to 1 as the prime grows, while `(k + 1)/k = 1 + 1/k` also gets closer to 1.\n\nBut in reality, for `k = 1`, they are equal (2 / 1 = 2 and 2 / 1 = 2). For `k = 2`, equal again (3 / 2 = 1.5, 3 / 2 = 1.5). For `k = 3`, `5 / 4 = 1.25` vs `4 / 3 ‚âà 1.333` (as before). It seems for `k ‚â• 3`, `(nthNat.Prime k) / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k` holds.\n\nBut this is not always true, because for `k = 6`, `nthNat.Prime 6 = 13`, `13 / 12 ‚âà 1.083`, `(6 + 1)/6 ‚âà 1.166`, so it holds, but for `k = 7`, `nthNat.Prime 7 = 17`, `17 / 16 ‚âà 1.0625`, `8 / 7 ‚âà 1.142`, holds again. \n\nIs there a good general estimate? \n\nAnother approach: Show that for every `k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x)`, we have:\n`nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k`, and then multiply all of these inequalities. \n\nBut how to prove that? \n\nFor `k = 1`, as above, both sides are 2. \n\nFor `k ‚â• 2`, we can rearrange:\n`(nthNat.Prime k) * k ‚â§ (nthNat.Prime k - 1)(k + 1)` \n`nthNat.Prime k * k ‚â§ nthNat.Prime k * k + nthNat.Prime k - k - 1`\n`0 ‚â§ nthNat.Prime k - k - 1`.\n\nBut `nthNat.Prime k - k - 1 ‚â• 0` is equivalent to `nthNat.Prime k ‚â• k + 1`, which is known for `k ‚â• 1`. \n\nTherefore, `nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k` for `k ‚â• 1`, because `nthNat.Prime k - 1 > 0`, and the cross-multiplication holds (as shown above).\n\nThus, each term in the product is ‚â§ the corresponding term in the other product. So the overall product is ‚â§.\n\nBut to formalize this: \n1. We need that for `k` in `Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x)`, `nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k` as natural numbers? Wait no, in Lean it's actually `Nat.div`, which is integer division. \n\nBut the Lean code uses `/` for `‚Ñï`, which is integer division, and then `‚Üë` casts it to reals. So perhaps it would be better to not use `/` but use `‚Üë` first to reals?\n\nWait no: in Lean, `nth Nat.Prime k` is a `‚Ñï`, and `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1)` is a `‚Ñï` if `nth Nat.Prime k - 1 > 0`, which it is for `k ‚â• 1`. Then `‚Üë` (the product as `‚àè` in ‚Ñï) will cast it to a `‚Ñù`.\n\nHowever, when we do `(k + 1) / k`, it's also `‚Ñï` division. For example, when `k = 1`, `(1 + 1)/1 = 2`; when `k = 2`, `(2 + 1)/2 = 3/2 = 1` as `‚Ñï`. \n\nBut earlier, for `k = 2`, `nth Nat.Prime 2 / (nth Nat.Prime 2 - 1) = 3 / 2 = 1`, and `(2 + 1)/2 = 3/2 = 1`, so `1 ‚â§ 1`.\n\nSimilarly for `k = 3`, `nth Nat.Prime 3 / (nth Nat.Prime 3 - 1) = 5 / 4 = 1`, and `(3 + 1)/3 = 4/3 = 1`, so `1 ‚â§ 1`.\n\nSimilarly for `k = 4`, `7 / 6 = 1`, `5/4 = 1`.\n\nBut for `k = 3`, if we do reals, `5/4 ‚â§ 4/3 ‚âà 1.333`, which is true. \n\nBut here in Lean, as naturals, we get `1 ‚â§ 1`. \n\nBut the issue is that when `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1)` is treated as naturals, we are losing precision, and we might not have `‚â§` in the way we want. \n\nThus, perhaps a better approach is to:\n1. Show that `primeCountingReal x ‚â• 1` (we might have to check this)\n2. Wrong approach, as it may not hold for division in `‚Ñï`\n\nAlternatively, perhaps in Lean, we need to not use `‚Ñï` division but rather coercions to `‚Ñù` first. \n\nWait no: the statement uses `/` in `‚Ñï`, and then coerces the product to `‚Ñù`. \n\nBut perhaps for every `k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x)`, in `‚Ñï`, `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k`, and then if the product is taken as `‚Ñï` products, and then coerced to `‚Ñù`, it will preserve the inequality.\n\nFor example: when `k = 1`: `2 / 1 = 2`, `(1 + 1)/1 = 2`: `2 ‚â§ 2`. \n\nFor `k = 2`: `3 / 2 = 1`, `(2 + 1)/2 = 1`: `1 ‚â§ 1`.\n\nFor `k = 3`: `5 / 4 = 1`, `(3 + 1)/3 = 1`: `1 ‚â§ 1`.\n\nFor `k = 4`: `7 / 6 = 1`, `5/4 = 1`: `1 ‚â§ 1`.\n\nFor `k = 5`: `11 / 10 = 1`, `6 / 5 = 1`: `1 ‚â§ 1`.\n\nThus, in `‚Ñï`, `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1)` is `1` for all `k ‚â• 2`. \n\nWait no: for `k = 1`, it's `2`, and `(k + 1)/k = 2`, so `2 ‚â§ 2`. \n\nThus, for each `k` in `Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x)`:\n\n1. If `k = 1`, then `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) = 2`, `(k + 1)/k = 2`, and `2 ‚â§ 2`.\n2. If `k ‚â• 2`, then `nth Nat.Prime k ‚â• k + 1`, thus:\n   - `nth Nat.Prime k - 1 ‚â• k`\n   - Then `nth Nat.Prime k < 2 * (nth Nat.Prime k - 1)` for primes `‚â• 3` (since it is equivalent to `nth Nat.Prime k > 2`)\n   - So `(nth Nat.Prime k) / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) = 1`, because `(nth Nat.Prime k - 1) * 1 ‚â§ nth Nat.Prime k < (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) * 2`.\n   - And `(k + 1)/k = 1` because `k ‚â• 1`.\n\nThus, in `‚Ñï`, the two sides are equal if `k ‚â• 2`, and equal to 2 if `k = 1`. \n\nTherefore, the product of `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1)` is ‚â§ the product of `(k + 1)/k` for all `k ‚àà Icc 1 m`, with `m = primeCountingReal x`. \n\n(Details: if `m = 0`, the product is 1, and we would have `Icc 1 0` empty, product is 1, but `primeCountingReal x ‚â• 1` probably, because `x` is large enough? Not sure. But if `m = 0`, `Icc 1 m = empty`, product is 1, and the same for the other side.)\n\nBut in the Lean statement, `‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x)` is a product in `‚Ñï` (since `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1)` is `‚Ñï` division), and then upcast to `‚Ñù`.\n\nBut the product of the first side in `‚Ñï` is ‚â§ product of second side in `‚Ñï`, because each term is ‚â§, so the product in `‚Ñï` is ‚â§, and then coercing to `‚Ñù` preserves it.\n\nThus, if `m = primeCountingReal x`, and we know that for each `k ‚àà Icc 1 m`, `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k`, then `‚àè ‚â§ ‚àè`, then `‚Üë(‚àè) ‚â§ ‚Üë(‚àè)`.\n\nTherefore, our task reduces to verifying that for each `k ‚àà Icc 1 m`, in `‚Ñï`, `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k`.\n\nBut for `k ‚â• 2`, we saw that `nth Nat.Prime k / (nth Nat.Prime k - 1) = 1`, and `(k + 1)/k = 1` because `k + 1 ‚â§ 2k`.\n\nFor `k = 1`, we have equality.\n\nTherefore, we can go in `‚Ñï`, prove that `nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k` for each `k`, and then the product will inherit it.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we could have done it in `‚Ñù`, but since Lean is using `/` in `‚Ñï`, we might as well stick to that. \n\n### Formal Proof Sketch\n\n1. For every `k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x)`:\n   - If `k = 1`: verify that `nth Nat.Prime 1 / (nth Nat.Prime 1 - 1) = 2` and `(1 + 1)/1 = 2`.\n   - If `k ‚â• 2`:",
      "‚Üë(‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1) / k) := by\n        have h‚ÇÅ : ‚àÄ (k : ‚Ñï), k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x) ‚Üí ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) : ‚Ñù) / ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù) ‚â§ ((k + 1 : ‚Ñï) : ‚Ñù) / (k : ‚Ñù) := by sorry\n        have h‚ÇÇ : (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñù) / ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù)) ‚â§ (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1 : ‚Ñù) / (k : ‚Ñù)) := by\n          apply Finset.prod_le_prod\n          ¬∑ intro k hk\n            have h‚ÇÉ : k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x) := hk\n            have h‚ÇÑ : 0 < (k : ‚Ñï) := by\n              simp [Finset.mem_Icc] at h‚ÇÉ\n              omega\n            have h‚ÇÖ : 0 < (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) := Nat.pos_of_ne_zero (by\n              intro h‚ÇÜ\n              have h‚Çá := (Nat.Prime.ne_zero (Nat.prime_nth_prime k))\n              simp_all [h‚ÇÜ]\n            )\n            have h‚ÇÜ : 0 < (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 := by\n              have h‚Çá : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• 2 := by\n                have h‚Çà := Nat.Prime.two_le (Nat.prime_nth_prime k)\n                linarith\n              omega\n            have h‚Çá : 0 < (k : ‚Ñù) := by positivity\n            have h‚Çà : 0 < ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) : ‚Ñù) := by positivity\n            have h‚Çâ : 0 < ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù) := by\n              norm_cast\n              <;> omega\n            positivity\n          ¬∑ intro k hk\n            exact h‚ÇÅ k hk\n        have h‚ÇÉ : (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñù) / ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù)) = (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñù) / ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù)) := rfl\n        have h‚ÇÑ : (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1 : ‚Ñù) / (k : ‚Ñù)) = (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1 : ‚Ñù) / (k : ‚Ñù)) := rfl\n        -- Use the established inequalities to prove the final step\n        have h‚ÇÖ : (‚Üë(‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1))) = (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñù) / ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù)) := by sorry\n        have h‚ÇÜ : (‚Üë(‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1) / k)) = (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1 : ‚Ñù) / (k : ‚Ñù)) := by sorry\n        calc\n          (‚Üë(‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1))) = (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñù) / ((nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 : ‚Ñù)) := by rw [h‚ÇÖ]\n          _ ‚â§ (‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1 : ‚Ñù) / (k : ‚Ñù)) := h‚ÇÇ\n          _ = (‚Üë(‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1) / k)) := by\n            rw [h‚ÇÜ]\n      _ ‚â§ ‚Üë(‚àè k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (k + 1) / k) := by sorry",
      "\n        have h‚ÇÅ : ‚àÄ k ‚àà Icc 1 (primeCountingReal x), (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1) / k := by\n          intro k hk\n          have h‚ÇÇ : 1 ‚â§ k := by\n            simp [Icc] at hk\n            linarith\n          have h‚ÇÉ : k ‚â§ primeCountingReal x := by\n            simp [Icc] at hk\n            linarith\n          have h‚ÇÑ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• k := by\n            have h‚ÇÖ : ‚àÄ n : ‚Ñï, n ‚â• 1 ‚Üí (nth Nat.Prime n : ‚Ñï) ‚â• n := by\n              intro n hn\n              induction' hn with n hn IH\n              ¬∑ simp [nth]\n              ¬∑ simp_all [nth, Nat.succ_eq_add_one, Nat.add_assoc]\n                <;>\n                (try decide) <;>\n                (try omega) <;>\n                (try nlinarith) <;>\n                (try\n                  {\n                    have h‚ÇÜ := Nat.Prime.one_lt (Nat.primes_list.get _)\n                    simp_all [List.get]\n                    <;>\n                    (try omega)\n                  })\n            exact h‚ÇÖ k (by omega)\n          have h‚ÇÖ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 ‚â• k - 1 := by\n            have h‚ÇÜ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• k := h‚ÇÑ\n            have h‚Çá : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 ‚â• k - 1 := by\n              have h‚Çà : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• k := h‚ÇÑ\n              have h‚Çâ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 ‚â• k - 1 := by\n                omega\n              exact h‚Çâ\n            exact h‚Çá\n          have h‚ÇÜ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1) / k := by\n            have h‚Çá : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• 2 := by\n              have h‚Çà : ‚àÄ n : ‚Ñï, n ‚â• 1 ‚Üí (nth Nat.Prime n : ‚Ñï) ‚â• 2 := by\n                intro n hn\n                induction' hn with n hn IH\n                ¬∑ simp [nth]\n                ¬∑ simp_all [nth, Nat.succ_eq_add_one, Nat.add_assoc]\n                  <;>\n                  (try decide) <;>\n                  (try omega) <;>\n                  (try nlinarith) <;>\n                  (try\n                    {\n                      have h‚Çâ := Nat.Prime.one_lt (Nat.primes_list.get _)\n                      simp_all [List.get]\n                      <;>\n                      (try omega)\n                    })\n              exact h‚Çà k (by omega)\n            have h‚Çà : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 ‚â• 1 := by\n              omega\n            have h‚Çâ : (k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• 1 := by\n              omega\n            have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) ‚â§ 2 := by\n              have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÅ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) ‚â§ 2 := by\n                apply Nat.le_of_lt_succ\n                have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) < 3 := by\n                  have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÉ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) - 1 > 0 := by omega\n                  have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÑ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) < 3 := by\n                    apply Nat.div_lt_of_lt_mul\n                    have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÖ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) < 3 * ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) := by\n                      have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÜ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) ‚â• 2 := h‚Çá\n                      have h‚ÇÅ‚Çá : 3 * ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) = 3 * ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) := rfl\n                      have h‚ÇÅ‚Çà : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) < 3 * ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) := by\n                        cases (nth Nat.Prime k) with\n                        | zero => omega\n                        | succ n =>\n                          cases n with\n                          | zero => omega\n                          | succ n =>\n                            simp_all [Nat.mul_succ]\n                            <;> ring_nf at *\n                            <;> nlinarith\n                      exact h‚ÇÅ‚Çà\n                    exact h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÖ\n                  exact h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÑ\n                omega\n              exact h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÅ\n            have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÅ : (k + 1 : ‚Ñï) / k ‚â• 1 := by\n              have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇ : (k + 1 : ‚Ñï) / k ‚â• 1 := by\n                have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÉ : (k + 1 : ‚Ñï) / k ‚â• 1 := by\n                  apply Nat.one_le_div_iff (by omega) |>.mpr\n                  <;> nlinarith\n                exact h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÉ\n              exact h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇ\n            have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇ : (nth Nat.Prime k : ‚Ñï) / ((nth Nat.Prime k) - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1) / k := by\n              cases k with\n              | zero =>\n                simp_all [Icc]\n              | succ k =>\n                cases k with\n                | zero =>\n                  norm_num [nth] at *\n                  <;>\n                  (try omega) <;>\n                  (try nlinarith)\n                | succ k =>\n                  simp_all [Icc]\n                  <;>\n                  (try omega) <;>\n                  (try nlinarith)\n                  <;>\n                  (try\n                    {\n                      have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÉ : (nth Nat.Prime (k + 2) : ‚Ñï) ‚â• (k + 2) := by\n                        have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÑ : ‚àÄ n : ‚Ñï, n ‚â• 1 ‚Üí (nth Nat.Prime n : ‚Ñï) ‚â• n := by\n                          intro n hn\n                          induction' hn with n hn IH\n                          ¬∑ simp [nth]\n                          ¬∑ simp_all [nth, Nat.succ_eq_add_one, Nat.add_assoc]\n                            <;>\n                            (try decide) <;>\n                            (try omega) <;>\n                            (try nlinarith) <;>\n                            (try\n                              {\n                                have h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÖ := Nat.Prime.one_lt (Nat.primes_list.get _)\n                                simp_all [List.get]\n                                <;>\n                                (try omega)\n                              })\n                        exact h‚ÇÅ‚ÇÑ (k + 2) (by omega)\n                      omega\n                    })\n                  <;>\n                  (try\n                    {\n                    