      "as equality.\n\n   We need to prove that `nthNat.Prime k / (nthNat.Prime k - 1) ‚â§ (k + 1)/k` for all `k ‚â• 1`.\n\n   To make this formal in Lean:\n   For `k ‚â• 1`, let `p = nthNat.Prime k`. Then `p ‚â• 2`.\n   - If `p = 2`, then `p - 1 = 1`, `p / (p - 1) = 2`, and `(k + 1)/k = 2/1 = 2` since `p = 2` implies `k = 1`.\n   - If `p >= 3`, then `p - 1 >= 2`, and `p / (p - 1) = 1` because `p < 2 * (p - 1)` for `p > 2`. Also, `(k + 1)/k = 1` because `k + 1 < 2k` when `k >= 2`.\n\n   But when `k = 2`, `p = 3`, `p / (p - 1) = 1`, and `(k + 1)/k = 3/2 = 1`, so it works. \n\n   And for `k = 3`, `p = 5`, `p / (p - 1) = 1`, `(k + 1)/k = 4/3 = 1`. \n\n   It is not so simple: let‚Äôs check for `k = 1` to `k = 6`.\n\n   - `k = 1`: `p = 2`, `p / (p - 1) = 2`, `(k + 1)/k = 2",
