      "for `n = 3`, `3 ‚â§ x < 4`, `‚åäx‚åã‚Çä = 3`, primes ‚â§ 3 are 2, 3, so `œÄ(3) = 2`, `primeCountingReal x = 2`. \nThe product is `p_1/(p_1 - 1) * p_2/(p_2 - 1) = 2/1 * 3/2 = 3`, and `(k + 1)/k = 2/1 * 3/2 = 3`. \n\nBut for `n = 4`, `4 ‚â§ x < 5`, `‚åäx‚åã‚Çä = 4`, primes ‚â§ 4 are 2,3, so `œÄ(4) = 2`, `primeCountingReal x = 2` and product is same as before. \n\nNow, for `n = 5`, `5 ‚â§ x < 6`, `‚åäx‚åã‚Çä = 5`, primes ‚â§ 5: 2,3,5, so `œÄ(5) = 3`. \n\nThen `‚àè_{k=1..3} (p_k)/(p_k - 1) = 2/1 * 3/2 * 5/4 = 15/4 = 3.75`, and `‚àè_{k=1..3} (k + 1)/k = 2/1 * 3/2 * 4/3 = 4`. \n\nThus, the inequality is `3.75 ‚â§ 4`, which holds. \n\nTherefore, the statement is correct as written, and we should try to prove it. \n\nHowever, we have to provide a general proof that for all `m ‚â• 0`, `‚àè_{k=1}^m (p_k)/(p_k - 1) ‚â§ ‚àè_{k=1}^m (k + 1)/k`, with `p_k` being the `k`-th prime. \n\nActually, looking back at the numerical examples:\n- For `m = 0`: both sides = 1.\n- For `m = 1`: 2 ‚â§ 2.\n- For `m = 2`: 3 ‚â§ 3.\n- For `m = 3`: 3.75 ‚â§ 4.\n- For `m = 4`: 3.75 * 7/6 ‚âà 4.375, 4 * 5/4 = 5 ‚Üí 4.375 ‚â§ 5.\n- For `m = 5`: 4.375 * 11/10 ‚âà 4.8125, 5 * 6/5 = 6 ‚Üí 4.8125 ‚â§ 6.\n\nIt appears that the inequality holds, and is tight at `m = 1`, `m = 2`. \n\nSo let's try a proof for `m ‚â• 1`.\n\nNote that for `k ‚â• 3`, `p_k/(p_k - 1) = 1 + 1/(p_k - 1) < 1 + 1/k`. \n\nBut `(k + 1)/k = 1 + 1/k`, and `(k + 1)/k ‚â• 1 + 1/(p_k - 1)` iff `1/k ‚â• 1/(p_k - 1)` iff `p_k - 1",
